WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.080 --> 00:00:00.800
For this session.

2
00:00:01.640 --> 00:00:05.520
I would like to first welcome you to this

3
00:00:05.560 --> 00:00:09.380
session on Precision Liver Cancer Care Across the Continuum, From

4
00:00:09.440 --> 00:00:10.860
Prevention to Therapy.

5
00:00:11.660 --> 00:00:15.080
My name is Valerie Chiu from Duke-NUS Medical School,

6
00:00:15.860 --> 00:00:19.500
and the chair for this session. It's a great honor and pleasure to be

7
00:00:19.580 --> 00:00:23.110
chairing this session and bringing together different

8
00:00:23.140 --> 00:00:27.090
perspectives from across Asia, Europe, and

9
00:00:27.120 --> 00:00:30.680
the United States. And what we'd like to call this session as the East

10
00:00:30.860 --> 00:00:33.860
Meet West Perspectives on Liver Cancer Care.

11
00:00:35.320 --> 00:00:39.240
HCC remain one of the leading causes of cancer-related

12
00:00:39.480 --> 00:00:40.700
death worldwide,

13
00:00:42.260 --> 00:00:45.500
and it is even predicted to increase by more than

14
00:00:45.680 --> 00:00:48.320
55% by the year 2040.

15
00:00:50.340 --> 00:00:54.320
Despite significant improvement in terms of cancer

16
00:00:54.420 --> 00:00:57.610
care, especially with the advancement in immunotherapy,

17
00:00:58.600 --> 00:01:00.500
the outcome remain highly valuable.

18
00:01:01.600 --> 00:01:05.500
So we really have a key challenge here because we believe HCC

19
00:01:05.780 --> 00:01:07.080
is not a single disease.

20
00:01:08.580 --> 00:01:12.420
And it is really a highly heterogeneous cancer, which is

21
00:01:12.460 --> 00:01:13.320
very hard to treat,

22
00:01:14.120 --> 00:01:17.860
and the cancer itself is shaped not only by the tumor intrinsic

23
00:01:18.080 --> 00:01:21.520
biology, but also by the underlying liver disease

24
00:01:22.020 --> 00:01:23.920
that is very heterogeneous in nature.

25
00:01:25.460 --> 00:01:27.960
And it also has the different immune contexts.

26
00:01:28.360 --> 00:01:32.000
And increasingly, we are seeing more and more metabolic-related liver

27
00:01:32.040 --> 00:01:35.880
disease that is causing this cancer.

28
00:01:35.920 --> 00:01:39.320
So what this means is that the one size fits all

29
00:01:39.360 --> 00:01:42.700
approaches are no longer sufficient to treat liver cancer.

30
00:01:43.740 --> 00:01:47.240
Instead, we are entering into an era where precision

31
00:01:47.280 --> 00:01:50.480
medicine is becoming more and more important.

32
00:01:51.140 --> 00:01:54.200
And this will span across the full disease continuum

33
00:01:54.960 --> 00:01:58.660
from identifying who is at risk, to understanding the

34
00:01:58.720 --> 00:02:02.600
biology and the mechanism, and finally, to tailor the

35
00:02:02.620 --> 00:02:05.340
precision medicine to treat our patients.

36
00:02:06.740 --> 00:02:10.560
And today's session is structured exactly to address this.

37
00:02:11.620 --> 00:02:15.180
We will begin first upstream with precision prevention

38
00:02:15.820 --> 00:02:19.510
by our first speaker, Professor Yujin Hosoda, who will

39
00:02:19.520 --> 00:02:23.120
focus on biomarkers-guided precision prevention of

40
00:02:23.160 --> 00:02:23.720
HCC.

41
00:02:24.720 --> 00:02:28.540
And then we'll move on to understanding the mechanism

42
00:02:28.680 --> 00:02:32.160
using advanced omics technology delivered by myself.

43
00:02:33.040 --> 00:02:36.860
And finally, we will end with the third speaker, who will talk about

44
00:02:36.920 --> 00:02:40.640
clinical integration and personalized care for liver cancer

45
00:02:40.680 --> 00:02:43.120
patients by Dr. Manon Aller.

46
00:02:44.380 --> 00:02:48.340
So with that, I think without further ado, we all believe that this is

47
00:02:48.420 --> 00:02:51.640
an important disease that we need to discuss herein.

48
00:02:52.260 --> 00:02:56.000
So we will begin with our first speaker, Professor Yujin

49
00:02:56.040 --> 00:02:59.420
Hosoda. Professor Hosoda is a clinician scientist

50
00:03:00.020 --> 00:03:03.660
and a professor of internal medicine, Director of Liver Tumor

51
00:03:03.760 --> 00:03:07.380
Translational Research, Co-director of Liver Cancer SPOR

52
00:03:07.500 --> 00:03:11.460
Program at University of Texas Southwestern Medical

53
00:03:11.580 --> 00:03:15.420
Center. So many titles there. And his work has been

54
00:03:15.500 --> 00:03:16.480
instrumental, really,

55
00:03:17.280 --> 00:03:21.040
in defining the molecular risk factors or signature for liver

56
00:03:21.140 --> 00:03:25.040
cancer, as you may all well known about this Hosoda

57
00:03:25.180 --> 00:03:27.820
et al. gene signature. So

58
00:03:28.100 --> 00:03:30.640
Professor Hosoda, please. Thank you.

59
00:03:35.960 --> 00:03:39.760
Thanks so much for having me and a very kind introduction, Professor

60
00:03:39.820 --> 00:03:41.980
Chiu. So let me start with

61
00:03:42.780 --> 00:03:43.900
the prevention things.

62
00:03:44.720 --> 00:03:48.480
I will talk about our ongoing works attempting

63
00:03:48.540 --> 00:03:52.320
to introduce a precision prevention strategy for HCC

64
00:03:52.460 --> 00:03:55.890
using the biomarker, and I'd love to hear your feedback and

65
00:03:56.000 --> 00:03:56.500
advice.

66
00:03:58.620 --> 00:03:59.420
My disclosure.

67
00:04:00.920 --> 00:04:04.600
So let me start from this, from a recent Lancet Commission article

68
00:04:04.840 --> 00:04:07.240
showing the overall survival change

69
00:04:08.060 --> 00:04:12.020
after the surgical treatment of HCC patients over the past six

70
00:04:12.080 --> 00:04:15.480
decades, starting from the oldest era,

71
00:04:15.980 --> 00:04:19.740
shown at the bottom blue line, with a 10-year overall survival

72
00:04:19.880 --> 00:04:23.680
of only 7%, which has been remarkably

73
00:04:23.720 --> 00:04:27.520
improved to nearly 60% in the most recent era, shown at the

74
00:04:27.560 --> 00:04:31.100
top by red line. This is a remarkable change, but

75
00:04:31.220 --> 00:04:32.340
still, this indicate

76
00:04:33.240 --> 00:04:35.520
HCC is not still the curable disease.

77
00:04:36.440 --> 00:04:40.100
This article also noted this gap is attributable to the failure of the

78
00:04:40.160 --> 00:04:44.080
prevention, and three out of five liver cancer cases can

79
00:04:44.160 --> 00:04:47.900
be theoretically preventable, otherwise, the number will be double

80
00:04:47.960 --> 00:04:49.080
by 2050.

81
00:04:50.720 --> 00:04:54.360
So, what kind of preventive intervention we can think about for

82
00:04:54.420 --> 00:04:57.980
HCC? So here I'm showing the natural history of HCC development,

83
00:04:58.200 --> 00:05:00.200
starting from the healthy liver here,

84
00:05:01.180 --> 00:05:05.020
exposed to the risk factor, HBV, HCV, alcohol, and metabolic

85
00:05:05.100 --> 00:05:08.060
disorders, and the liver gradually develop the

86
00:05:08.640 --> 00:05:12.200
accumulating liver fibrosis, chronic inflammation, which

87
00:05:12.280 --> 00:05:14.800
eventually lead to the terminal stage cirrhosis here.

88
00:05:15.380 --> 00:05:16.800
Then cancer starts to arise.

89
00:05:18.300 --> 00:05:21.720
Along with the natural history, we can think about the preventive

90
00:05:21.780 --> 00:05:23.580
intervention at the different levels.

91
00:05:23.760 --> 00:05:27.500
For example, the primary aims to prevent the exposure to the risk factor.

92
00:05:28.300 --> 00:05:32.080
We do HPV vaccination to infants, which is shown to be

93
00:05:32.140 --> 00:05:35.000
very effective to reduce HCC incidence.

94
00:05:35.900 --> 00:05:39.440
Secondary prevention. We do regular HCC screen for early

95
00:05:39.480 --> 00:05:42.100
detection, followed by the curative therapy.

96
00:05:42.900 --> 00:05:45.760
And we know antiviral therapies

97
00:05:45.840 --> 00:05:49.790
significantly reduce HCC incidence, but does not

98
00:05:49.840 --> 00:05:52.840
eliminate the cancer incidence in some patients.

99
00:05:54.400 --> 00:05:57.820
Tertiary prevention kicks in after the initial diagnosis of the cancer.

100
00:05:58.230 --> 00:06:02.190
And what we can do is only recurrence monitoring therapy at this moment, and

101
00:06:02.260 --> 00:06:06.060
we are still waiting for the neoadjuvant adjuvant therapy becomes

102
00:06:06.120 --> 00:06:10.088
available.So in this talk, I will talk about unmet

103
00:06:10.168 --> 00:06:14.008
needs in the secondary prevention, which is a refined screening and the

104
00:06:14.048 --> 00:06:17.708
chemo prevention. And then you will learn about the later stage

105
00:06:17.748 --> 00:06:21.308
treatment of HCC from Professor Cho and Professor Alya

106
00:06:21.328 --> 00:06:22.548
later in this session.

107
00:06:23.568 --> 00:06:25.927
So, first topic, HCC screening.

108
00:06:26.928 --> 00:06:30.868
So this is what we do for the regular HCC screening recommended in the

109
00:06:30.928 --> 00:06:34.808
guidelines. Here is the target population, cirrhosis, and the red

110
00:06:34.888 --> 00:06:38.348
people are indicating the people who will develop cancer during the

111
00:06:38.448 --> 00:06:39.508
irregular screening.

112
00:06:40.448 --> 00:06:43.788
So we do semiannual screening with ultrasound and AFP,

113
00:06:44.928 --> 00:06:48.548
but this recommended protocol is poorly utilized in the

114
00:06:48.628 --> 00:06:51.308
US, representing the US perspective.

115
00:06:51.948 --> 00:06:55.768
So the real utilization rate is less than 25%, which would be much,

116
00:06:55.828 --> 00:06:58.548
much higher in the Asian country like Singapore and Europe.

117
00:07:00.188 --> 00:07:03.368
But this is our real-world capability in the US.

118
00:07:03.648 --> 00:07:06.988
So, this is what we propose to do as a

119
00:07:07.308 --> 00:07:11.208
solution, which is a risk-stratified screening, which is impressed in

120
00:07:11.228 --> 00:07:13.648
the hepatology paper led by Dr. Kanwal,

121
00:07:14.528 --> 00:07:18.178
under the NCI-supported Translational Liver Cancer, or TLC,

122
00:07:18.288 --> 00:07:22.208
consortium. So here's the idea. So you do the risk

123
00:07:22.248 --> 00:07:25.858
prediction upfront and stratify the patients into these risk groups,

124
00:07:26.068 --> 00:07:27.728
high, intermediate, low risk group.

125
00:07:28.438 --> 00:07:32.148
And then tailor the priority and the intensity of the screening modality

126
00:07:32.708 --> 00:07:36.688
like this. For example, for low-risk people, you may apply low-performance

127
00:07:36.768 --> 00:07:38.608
and low-cost test or do nothing.

128
00:07:39.668 --> 00:07:42.968
Intermediate risk, you may stick to the current regular tests,

129
00:07:43.608 --> 00:07:47.528
and the high-risk people may be justifiable to be followed by high-performance and

130
00:07:47.648 --> 00:07:50.568
high-cost tests based on the anticipated higher yield.

131
00:07:51.688 --> 00:07:55.348
And this approach found to be very cost-effective in a simulation

132
00:07:55.388 --> 00:07:58.908
analysis compared to the one-size-fits-all screening and especially risk in

133
00:07:58.948 --> 00:08:01.588
the situation in the US we are facing.

134
00:08:03.248 --> 00:08:05.508
And what kind of risk stratification tools we have?

135
00:08:05.928 --> 00:08:09.668
So we have numbers of clinical variable-based scores that are listed here.

136
00:08:09.848 --> 00:08:13.128
This part shows the five-year AURLC for the risk

137
00:08:13.188 --> 00:08:16.937
prediction. And some of the scores are actually incorporated in the

138
00:08:16.988 --> 00:08:19.908
clinical practice. For example, the PAGE-B score in the middle,

139
00:08:21.308 --> 00:08:25.028
which definitely helps identify high-risk people, especially in the

140
00:08:25.048 --> 00:08:28.988
hepatitis B-infected patients. But still, as you see in the top

141
00:08:29.028 --> 00:08:32.447
part of the bar, there is still the room for the improvement.

142
00:08:32.948 --> 00:08:36.828
That's why many people are working on a biomarker discovery and development using

143
00:08:36.848 --> 00:08:40.828
the molecular information or imaging-based information or

144
00:08:40.869 --> 00:08:44.438
more recently, the histology-based information with the emergence of

145
00:08:44.528 --> 00:08:48.308
digital pathology combined with the deep learning methods, which can be

146
00:08:48.368 --> 00:08:52.158
also utilized for the clinical data or patient-derived electronical

147
00:08:52.248 --> 00:08:52.508
data.

148
00:08:54.248 --> 00:08:57.988
And here, let me show the one example, such a potential HCC

149
00:08:58.028 --> 00:09:01.988
risk biomarker we are working on, which is the HCC risk signature in

150
00:09:02.028 --> 00:09:05.968
the liver tissue, which we call PLS, prognostic liver signature, or

151
00:09:06.048 --> 00:09:09.088
it's a serum protein version, which we call PLS-Sec,

152
00:09:10.268 --> 00:09:13.988
stands for the prognostic liver secretome signature, validated in the

153
00:09:14.048 --> 00:09:16.448
multicenter prospective cohorts in the US.

154
00:09:17.148 --> 00:09:21.048
So here I'm showing the validation in the prospective cohort in the state of

155
00:09:21.088 --> 00:09:24.868
Texas, which enroll more than 2,000 patients, which nicely

156
00:09:24.948 --> 00:09:28.408
stratify the patient according to the risk level, which is

157
00:09:29.088 --> 00:09:32.208
associated with the actual real-world HCC incidents,

158
00:09:33.008 --> 00:09:36.888
which was replicated in a nationwide cohort called heads supported by

159
00:09:36.948 --> 00:09:38.528
NIH NCI

160
00:09:39.348 --> 00:09:41.948
in enrolling the more than 1,300 patients.

161
00:09:42.828 --> 00:09:46.668
So this is a promising finding, and this is a more recent simulation

162
00:09:46.748 --> 00:09:49.968
analysis we published led by my clinical colleague, Amy Stengel,

163
00:09:50.588 --> 00:09:53.368
which we call the precision HCC screening.

164
00:09:54.048 --> 00:09:57.708
So here we are looking at not only the biomarker but also

165
00:09:57.748 --> 00:10:01.608
incorporating patient factors such as patient sex, liver disease,

166
00:10:01.688 --> 00:10:04.408
etiology, severity, and the metabolic status.

167
00:10:04.968 --> 00:10:08.628
And in this exercise, this tailored screening is way more

168
00:10:08.688 --> 00:10:12.468
cost-effective or cost-saving and extending the patient's

169
00:10:12.528 --> 00:10:13.048
survival.

170
00:10:13.968 --> 00:10:17.508
So, with the emergence of AI and IT technology,

171
00:10:17.988 --> 00:10:21.868
we are hopeful to implement this very complicated algorithm

172
00:10:21.878 --> 00:10:23.028
sometime in the near future.

173
00:10:24.208 --> 00:10:27.468
So the second part, chemo prevention.

174
00:10:28.468 --> 00:10:32.278
So, we all know clinical development of preventive,

175
00:10:32.488 --> 00:10:34.828
chemopreventive strategies is very challenging.

176
00:10:34.898 --> 00:10:38.588
So I'm showing the series of failed HCC chemo prevention trials.

177
00:10:38.698 --> 00:10:41.908
The major effort enrolling more than 100 patients,

178
00:10:42.448 --> 00:10:46.278
testing the variety of agents, interferon, COX-2 inhibitor,

179
00:10:46.828 --> 00:10:49.068
a cyclic retinoid, or M2 inhibitor.

180
00:10:49.748 --> 00:10:53.308
So these are well-supported by convincing preclinical

181
00:10:53.868 --> 00:10:56.468
clinical data or retrospective data.

182
00:10:57.108 --> 00:10:57.908
But all

183
00:10:58.728 --> 00:11:02.168
failed to demonstrate clinically appreciable chemopreventive effect.

184
00:11:02.908 --> 00:11:05.968
So these trial, chemo prevention trials are highly demanding,

185
00:11:06.268 --> 00:11:10.028
require large sample size and a longer follow-up time compared to the

186
00:11:10.088 --> 00:11:13.988
typical oncology trial, despite the very

187
00:11:14.028 --> 00:11:15.068
low success rate.

188
00:11:16.468 --> 00:11:20.068
Now you may wonder, are the choice of the targets and agent may be wrong

189
00:11:20.348 --> 00:11:23.508
despite the ample supporting preclinical evidences.

190
00:11:23.868 --> 00:11:27.588
So the question is, which are the clinically relevant chemoprevention targets and

191
00:11:27.668 --> 00:11:28.088
agents?

192
00:11:29.248 --> 00:11:32.888
So in literature, you can see many plausible

193
00:11:33.168 --> 00:11:34.428
chemoprevention targets

194
00:11:35.268 --> 00:11:38.008
around the mechanism of hepatocarcinogenesis.

195
00:11:38.588 --> 00:11:42.208
So we believe the matured hepatocyte is a cell of origin for

196
00:11:42.288 --> 00:11:45.148
HCC transforming into the HCC cell.

197
00:11:45.188 --> 00:11:48.608
With the involvement of multiple cell types, we will hear about

198
00:11:48.928 --> 00:11:52.117
Professor Chu after my talk. There are many,

199
00:11:52.288 --> 00:11:55.348
the anti-protumor immune cells or

200
00:11:55.388 --> 00:11:57.398
immunosuppressive immune cell types.

201
00:11:58.088 --> 00:12:01.888
And also another major cell type is a hepatic stellate cell, which is the liver's

202
00:12:02.068 --> 00:12:05.508
pericytes responsible for the wound-healing response,

203
00:12:06.148 --> 00:12:10.138
which transdifferentiated to the cell phenotype called the myofibroblast,

204
00:12:10.228 --> 00:12:13.548
which is responsible for the production of collagen tissue,

205
00:12:13.768 --> 00:12:17.508
extracellular matrix protein, and which directly or indirectly

206
00:12:17.588 --> 00:12:21.316
influence the process of the transformation.And outside the liver,

207
00:12:21.976 --> 00:12:25.766
we know from the studies, gut dysbiosis transmitting the

208
00:12:25.836 --> 00:12:29.476
signal, and also the systemic adipose tissue affect the

209
00:12:29.976 --> 00:12:31.896
system, the transformation.

210
00:12:32.966 --> 00:12:36.836
And you can also find a series of many potential

211
00:12:36.876 --> 00:12:40.576
compounds and drugs that may inhibit the process as a

212
00:12:40.596 --> 00:12:43.336
possible chemoprevention agent, especially

213
00:12:43.456 --> 00:12:47.256
anti-metabolic disease therapy or anti-obesity therapy may have

214
00:12:47.316 --> 00:12:48.276
a great potential.

215
00:12:49.236 --> 00:12:52.356
However, even if you can come up with a plausible

216
00:12:52.456 --> 00:12:54.976
biology by targeting any of those targets,

217
00:12:56.136 --> 00:12:59.916
one caveat is that plausible biology is not necessarily equal to

218
00:12:59.936 --> 00:13:02.576
clinically meaningful cancer preventive targets.

219
00:13:03.556 --> 00:13:07.376
So you may wonder, what is a reliable molecular readout to

220
00:13:07.476 --> 00:13:11.196
monitor dynamic change in HCC risk level in

221
00:13:11.236 --> 00:13:14.676
response to any of this therapy as a surrogate endpoint in the real-world

222
00:13:14.736 --> 00:13:15.276
patients?

223
00:13:16.816 --> 00:13:20.316
So going back to the well-validated HCC risk biomarker

224
00:13:21.056 --> 00:13:25.036
just showed in the previous slide, we wonder if this biomarker can

225
00:13:25.056 --> 00:13:26.836
serve as such a surrogate endpoint.

226
00:13:27.336 --> 00:13:31.116
And then we ask if this biomarker-based risk level can be modulated by

227
00:13:31.156 --> 00:13:34.976
the therapeutic intervention known to reduce HCC incidence.

228
00:13:35.536 --> 00:13:39.416
For example, anti-HBV drug, which are known to significantly reduce

229
00:13:39.496 --> 00:13:43.336
HCC incidence. And in these 19 patients, we had a

230
00:13:43.356 --> 00:13:46.936
chance to analyze the changes in the biomarker before and after the antivirus

231
00:13:46.996 --> 00:13:50.616
therapy. And these patients all successfully cured the virus.

232
00:13:51.476 --> 00:13:54.316
And this bar plot or waterfall plot, if you will,

233
00:13:55.496 --> 00:13:58.516
y-axis is measuring the change in the biomarker risk level.

234
00:13:58.556 --> 00:14:02.496
And when the bar goes down, that means a reduction in the HCC risk level by the

235
00:14:02.516 --> 00:14:06.076
biomarker, which is seen in roughly 80% of the patients.

236
00:14:07.096 --> 00:14:10.966
And subsequent HCC incidence is significantly correlated with the

237
00:14:10.996 --> 00:14:14.076
change of the biomarker over 20 years of clinical follow-up.

238
00:14:15.496 --> 00:14:17.336
This may be only antiviral therapies.

239
00:14:18.516 --> 00:14:22.316
Statins are also suggested as a potential chemopreventive

240
00:14:22.456 --> 00:14:26.316
agent with association with a significantly lower HCC

241
00:14:26.356 --> 00:14:30.216
incidence in retrospective studies, particularly for lipophilic

242
00:14:30.276 --> 00:14:33.766
but not hydrophilic statin. And when we look at the change of the

243
00:14:33.856 --> 00:14:37.816
biomarker, indeed we see the improvement of the biomarker in

244
00:14:37.856 --> 00:14:40.776
the lipophilic statin users but not the hydrophilic users.

245
00:14:42.516 --> 00:14:46.256
Bariatric surgery is another intervention known to be associated with a

246
00:14:46.316 --> 00:14:50.296
lower HCC incidence. And similarly, we saw

247
00:14:50.356 --> 00:14:53.176
biomarker improvement that is associated with bariatric surgery.

248
00:14:53.996 --> 00:14:57.636
And a more recent drug, anti-obesity drug, GLP-1 receptor

249
00:14:57.696 --> 00:14:58.736
agonist and so forth,

250
00:14:59.836 --> 00:15:03.776
we wonder if it apply to this new class of agents.

